      "role": "user",
      "content": "thanks this is a good start. a bit on the dry side tho. can u make it sound a little more warm/empathetic without sounding unprofessional? like, emphasize that it was a really tough call for the hiring team because we were genuinely impressed. we really want to leave them with a positive impression of the company culture.",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Oh, you're right, the previous draft felt a bit too stiff, like a robot trying to be friendly! Let's inject some warmth and empathy, but we have to be careful not to sound *too* casual, or the \"gibberish\" might get in the way of the message.\n\nHere is a revised version that sounds more human and empathetic, while still keeping that professional edge. I've added a few little notes about how the hiring team felt, like they were trying to balance a scale of talent, but the weight of the distributed systems requirement tipped it just a little too far.\n\n***\n\n**Subject:** A Personal Note Regarding Your Senior Developer Application\n\nDear **[Candidate Name]**,\n\nFirst off, thank you for making the time to interview with us. We genuinely enjoyed our conversations and were truly impressed by your technical depth and the way you fit into our team's vibe.\n\nI want to be completely transparent: this was a really tough call for the hiring team. We were so close to making an offer to you! However, after reviewing the final candidates, we found ourselves leaning toward another applicant who had a bit more specific experience with our complex distributed systems challenges. It wasn't a decision made lightly",
